You can do this by creating extending the unbounded LinkedBlockingQueue with an implementation which enforce a capacity on the underlying unbounded queue. This gives you a resizable work queue for your thread pool.

First, you&#39;ll need to create the resizable implementation

    class ResizableBlockingQueue&lt;E&gt; extends LinkedBlockingQueue&lt;E&gt; {

        private int maxCapacity;

        public ResizableBlockingQueue(int maxCapacity) {
            this.maxCapacity = maxCapacity;
        }

        public int getMaxCapacity() {
            return maxCapacity;
        }

        public void setMaxCapacity(int maxCapacity) {
            this.maxCapacity = maxCapacity;
        }

        @Override public int remainingCapacity() {
            return getMaxCapacity() - size();
        }

        @Override public boolean offer(E e) {
            if (remainingCapacity() &lt;= 0) {
                return false;
            }
            return super.offer(e);
        }
    }

and now you can use it like this
 
    ResizableBlockingQueue&lt;Runnable&gt; executionQueue = new ResizableBlockingQueue&lt;&gt;(QUEUE_SIZE);
    ThreadPoolExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolExecutor(MIN_THREADS, MAX_THREADS, 30, TimeUnit.SECONDS, executionQueue);

    // Need a bigger work queue
    executionQueue.setMaxCapacity(BIGGER_QUEUE_SIZE);

As you can see, by this design, setting a smaller capacity will not remove existing work from the queue but will prevent new work from being enqueued until the queue size falls below the new `maxCapacity`

Enjoy!

